---
import MainLayout from '../../../layouts/MainLayout.astro';
import MotuSidebar from '../../../components/MotuSidebar.astro';
const title = "Tuner & Analysis Tools";
---
<MainLayout title={title}>
  <div class="flex gap-8 items-start">
    <div class="w-[250px] flex-shrink-0">
      <MotuSidebar />
    </div>
    <article class="prose max-w-none">
      <h1>{title}</h1>
      <p>Source: <a href="https://motu.com/products/motuaudio/ultralite-mk3/cuemix-fx-overview.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener">MOTU product page</a></p>

      <p>The Analysis tab in CueMix FX provides a suite of real-time meters and diagnostic tools. All run in hardware via the MOTU's internal DSP, adding no computer CPU load.</p>

      <h2>FFT Display</h2>
      <p>Real-time full-screen frequency spectrum analyser. The horizontal axis is frequency (20 Hz–20 kHz); the vertical axis is amplitude. Use it to:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Identify resonant frequencies in the Hydrasynth stereo output that may need EQ reduction before mixing.</li>
        <li>Check if the SM58 pickup has problematic room modes (narrow spikes in the low-mid range) that need a targeted parametric notch.</li>
        <li>Verify that the hi-pass filter in CueMix FX EQ is actually removing sub-bass energy from the vocal channel.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Spectrogram Waterfall</h2>
      <p>A time-plus-frequency display that scrolls over time, showing where energy appears in the frequency domain moment-to-moment. Excellent for checking reverb tails — if the hall reverb extends too long in the low-mid range, it shows clearly as coloured energy persisting after the source note ends.</p>

      <h2>Oscilloscope</h2>
      <p>Shows the actual waveform shape of the signal in real time. Use it to:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Verify the VT-3 output doesn't have DC offset (a waveform centred above or below zero).</li>
        <li>Check that the SM58 signal shape is clean and not clipping (visible as flat tops on waveform peaks).</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>X-Y Plot (Lissajous Figure)</h2>
      <p>Plots the left channel on the X axis and right channel on the Y axis. The shape reveals stereo content:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Diagonal line (45°):</strong> both channels are identical — perfectly mono signal.</li>
        <li><strong>Diagonal ellipse:</strong> normal stereo with some correlation — will collapse well to mono.</li>
        <li><strong>Wide horizontal blob:</strong> very wide stereo field; may lose information when collapsed to mono. Verify mono compatibility before printing.</li>
        <li><strong>X-shaped or horizontal:</strong> suggests phase issues — investigate cabling or processing chain.</li>
      </ul>
      <p>Check the HS7 output's X-Y figure to verify stereo correlation of the final mix before bouncing.</p>

      <h2>Chromatic Tuner</h2>
      <p>A chromatic tuner that monitors any selected input in real time. Before each session:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Route the Hydrasynth mono output to a MOTU input.</li>
        <li>Play a reference note (A3) on the Hydrasynth.</li>
        <li>Tune the Hydrasynth's Master Tuning to A=440 Hz using the tuner display.</li>
        <li>If using the P-225 alongside the Hydrasynth, ensure both instruments are tuned to the same reference before the session starts.</li>
      </ul>

      <figure>
        <img src="https://cdn-data.motu.com/site/images/cuemix-fx/fft.gif" alt="CueMix FX FFT analysis display" />
        <figcaption>Official MOTU-hosted FFT analysis image.</figcaption>
      </figure>
    </article>
  </div>
</MainLayout>
